overview.html.title: Overview
overview.html.body:
Overview
Mind Studio is an AI full-stack development platform developed based on Huawei's neural-network processing unit （NPU）. On Mind Studio, you can develop chip-based operators, and develop custom operators. Network migration, optimization, and analysis at the network layer is also supported. In addition, the service engine layer provides a set of visualized AI engine drag-and-drop programming services, which greatly reduces the AI engine development threshold. The entire platform provides the following four services for developers in a Web manner.

For operator development:
Mind Studio provides development of a full set of operators. It supports running in a real environment, visualized debugging of heterogeneous programs that are dynamically scheduled and third-party operator development, greatly reducing the operator development threshold based on Huawei-developed NPUs, improving the efficiency of operator development and enhancing product competitiveness.

For development at the network layer:
Mind Studio integrates the offline model conversion tool （OMG）, model quantization tool, model running profiling tool, and log analysis tool, greatly improving the efficiency of migration, analysis and optimization of network models.

For AI engine development:
Mind Studio provides the AI engine that supports visualized drag-and-drop programming and a large number of automatic algorithm code generation technologies, largely reducing the threshold for developers. Mind Studio is equipped with various algorithm engines, such as ResNet-18, boosting the development and migration efficiency of the user AI algorithm engine.

For application development:
Mind Studio integrates various tools, such as Profile and Compiler, providing a graphically integrated development environment. Developers can perform full-process development on Mind Studio, covering project management, compilation, commissioning, simulation, and performance analysis, greatly enhancing the development efficiency.

function-description.html.title: Function Description
function-description.html.body:
Function Description
Overall Architecture
Figure 1  shows the overall architecture of Mind Studio.
Figure  1  Overall architecture of Mind Studio
Function Description
Mind Studio provides the following features:

User-friendly NPU-based programming GUI
Operator developers can customize CCE development on Mind Studio based on the CCE programming depth to implement in-depth integration. The keywords of the extended CCE language are highlighted. You can compile heterogeneous hybrid codes in one-click mode.

NPU-based graphical debugging
For the development of the operator acceleration library on the NPU, Mind Studio provides a graphical GUI for users to implement real-time tracking of the running status of the acceleration operators on the AI core and AI CPU.

Automatic offline model management
Trained third-party models, such as Caffe and TensorFlow models, can be imported to Mind Studio and converted into models supported by the system. Model interfaces are generated automatically in one-click mode, enabling interface-based model programming. For details, see 4 "Offline Model Conversion" in the  Mind Studio Quick Start.

"Zero" programming for service process orchestration
For service process developers, Mind Studio provides the drag-and-drop programming mode based on service nodes. You can implement service orchestration by simply dragging and connecting service nodes. The one-stop service after orchestration, ranging from compilation and running to result display, makes process development smarter. "Zero" programming is involved. In this way, you can get started quickly without extra learning costs. For details, see 3 "Building the First Machine Learning App" in the  Mind Studio Quick Start  .

Graphical TE programming
Mind Studio provides the industry's first integrated development environment based on the TVM-based Tensor Engine （TE） for programming development. Operators can be transplanted quickly across platforms, enabling instant NPU adaption.

Log Analysis
Mind Studio provides a system-wide log collection and analysis solution for the NPU platform, improving the efficiency of locating runtime algorithm problems. A unified log format is adopted. Visualized analysis of cross-platform logs and runtime diagnosis runs in Web mode, improving the usability of the log analysis system.

Performance analysis
Mind Studio provides graphical user interfaces （GUIs） and command-line interfaces (CLIs) to implement efficient, easy-to-use, and flexible performance profiling on the multi-node and multi-module heterogeneous system on the host and device. Synchronous analysis of performance and power consumption of the NPU device is implemented, which meets the requirements of algorithm optimization for system performance analysis.

Simulation
Function-level simulation execution libraries for the AI core under the Caffe framework are provided. You can call AI core simulation by using the program.

logging-in.html.body:
Logging In
Figure 1  shows the login page.
Figure  1  Login page
Table 1  describes the parameters on the page.
Table  1  Parameters on the login page

Parameter

Description



User Name

Login user name. The default value is MindStudioAdmin. You cannot change it or create a new one.


Password

Login password. The initial password is Huawei123@.
Password requirements:
The password contains 8 to 16 characters.The password contains at least one uppercase or lowercase letter.The password contains at least one digit.The password contains at least one of the following special characters: ~!@#$%^&*()_-=+|\[]{}:;,<>/? NOTE: If you have entered incorrect passwords for three consecutive times within 5 minutes, a message will be displayed indicating that the login is locked. Try again in 30 minutes.The password can be used within the 90-day validity period. If the password expires, a message will be displayed to prompt you to change the password. See Figure 2.




Login

Login. Enter the correct user name and password, and click this button. The Mind Studio GUI is displayed.


Modify


Password modification. If you want to change the password after logging in to Mind Studio, click this button. For details, see Changing the Password.





Figure  2  Message indicating that the password expires
Enter the correct password and click  Login.

If you are logging in for the first time, the password resetting page is displayed. For details, see  Resetting the Password.
If you are logging in not for the first time, the  Login Information  dialog box as shown in  Figure 3  is displayed. Click  OK, the Mind Studio GUI is displayed.
Figure  3  Login Information
Whether the last login succeeds, the login time, IP address of the login user, number of login attempts, and password validity period are displayed.

If no operation is performed within 30 minutes after a successful login, a message will be displayed indicating that the session times out and the user will be forced to log out. In this case, the user needs to enter the password again to log in.
The login timeout period  SessionTimeOut  is configurable. You can change the value of it in the  ~/tools/conf/mind_studio.config  file. The valid value range is 5 to 1440 （minute）. The default value is  30  minutes. If this parameter is set to  –1, the session never times out. If the configured value is not in the valid range, the default value  30 is used.

After you successfully log in to Mind Studio, multiple Mind Studio tabs can be opened on the same browser on the same client. However, you are advised to use Mind Studio on a single tab page. Operations on multiple tabs may cause exceptions.

If the current user is logged in and the same user name and password are used to log in to Mind Studio on a different client, the current user will be forced to log out.
If the server is shut down, the message shown in  Figure 4  is displayed when you log in to the server.
Figure  4  Server unavailable page
If the preceding information is displayed, go to the log file in the tools directory （the default path is  $HOME/tools） and check the  mind_log  file to see whether the Mind Studio background service is stopped. If yes, restart Mind Studio.

overview-1.html.title: Overview
overview-1.html.body:
Overview
Datasets are classified into built-in datasets and custom datasets （my datasets）. Built-in datasets can be directly used by dragging. Custom datasets need to be manually imported. The properties of custom datasets are stored in MongoDB, and the files imported by users are stored in the file system.

Built-in datasets:
Mind Studio provides built-in datasets. They can be used in Mind projects created by users. Built-in datasets exist before a workspace is created. You can use them but cannot add, delete, or modify them.
Currently only one built-in dataset is available:
MnistDataset: It is the most commonly used dataset for reasonableness check. It consists of 28 x 28 black and white images of handwritten digits. The digits are displayed in the center of each image. MNIST is a simple task. Passing the MNIST test does not necessarily indicate that a model can operate effectively.

My datasets:
You can create your own datasets by saving sets of images as custom datasets for future use. A newly created workspace has no custom datasets. Custom datasets can be added or deleted but cannot be modified.
The images of a custom dataset can be obtained from local files and local folders.

overview-3.html.body:
Overview
Models are classified into built-in models, custom models, and Caffe models.

Built-in models:
Built-in models are preset in Mind Studio and exist before a workspace is created. You can use them but cannot add, delete, or modify them.
The currently available built-in model is ResNet-18.

Custom models:
A custom model （such as a Caffe or TensorFlow model） can be added to Mind Studio by using the offline conversion function for future use. A newly created workspace has no custom models. You can add a custom model by model conversion or simply adding one.

Caffe models:
After a Caffe model is added on the orchestration window, the Caffe model is added to  Model Zoo. A newly created workspace has no Caffe models.

Click    on the right of  Model File  to select a model file.
See  Figure 3.

The name of the model file is automatically filled in the  Model Name  text box. After selecting a model file, you can change the model name as required.
The tool parses the model file and obtains the default  Input Shape  of the model. （A TensorFlow model or a model with a custom layer does not support parsing. In this case, you can enter the content in the  Input Shape  text box. The format of a Caffe model is input_name:n,c,h,w. The format of a TensorFlow model is  input_name:n,h,w,c. Multiple inputs need to be separated by semicolons (;）. For example:  data1:1,3,224,224;data2:1,3,32,32


After you select a model file, the    button is displayed on the right of  Model File. Click this button. The original network structure of the model is displayed. See  Figure 4.

Parameter

Description

Options: YUV420SP_U8, XRGB8888_U8, and RGB888_U8.

Encrypting and Decrypting a Custom Model 
By encrypting models, model developers can control the use of models. They can use the encryption function to obtain the encrypted offline model and key. Only users with the encrypted model and key can use the model.
An encrypted model can run only in a Mind project whose  Target  is set to  ASIC  or  Atlas DK.
Encrypting a Model

Select a project, choose  Tools > Convert Model, or click    of  My Models  on the  tool tab page.
Expand  Optional Options  and turn  Encryption on, as shown in  Figure 1.

Enter the password. The encryption system uses this password to generate a unique key, which is used as an input for encryption.

If you have entered a password for the workspace, the previous password is used by default. You can also choose to a new password, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Use Last Password

Upload the ISV hardware key, ISV certificate, and ISV private key, as shown in  Figure 3.

After the model conversion is successful, a dialog box is displayed, indicating that the conversion is successful, as shown in  Figure 4.  Offline Model Path  indicates the path of the encrypted file.
Figure  4  Successful conversion dialog box
Log in to the server where the Mind Studio tool is located. You can view the encrypted model file and passcode file in the path indicated by  Offline Model Path.

Drag the offline model to the orchestration canvas and go to the  property tab page, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Model property tab page

Set  Decryption  to on, select the passcode file, and decrypt the model.

omg --model=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/resnet18.prototxt --weight=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/resnet18.caffemodel --framework=0 --output=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/out/caffe_resnet18 --encrypt_mode=0 --encrypt_key=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/ek_key --hardware_key=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/isv_hw_key --certificate=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/isv_cert.crt --private_key=/usr/local/HiAI/driver/tools/test/isv_prikey.key

aipp-configuration.html.title: AIPP Configuration
aipp-configuration.html.body:
AIPP Configuration
With  Input Image Preprocess  enabled during offline model conversion （for details, see the description of the  Optional Options  parameters in 5.2.1.1 "Adding a Custom Model Component"）, after the model conversion is complete, you can view the parameter configurations in the  convertModel.log  file of the project.
The following describes the configuration file.
#
# The AIPP provides the following features: color space conversion (CSC), crop, mean reduction, multiplication coefficient, data switching between channels, and single-line mode.
# The input images must in UINT8 format.
# To use this configuration file, delete the parameter comments to be configured and set the parameter values as required.
# The parameter values in the template are default values. The input_format attribute is mandatory, while other attributes are optional.
#

#========================= Global settings =========================

# Input image format
# Type: enum
# Value: YUV420SP_U8, XRGB8888_U8, RGB888_U8, or YUV400_U8
# input_format :

# CSC switch
# Type: bool
# Value: true or false
# csc_switch :false

# Image width and height
# Type: uint13
# Value range: (0, 4096]. For YUV420SP_U8 images, the value must be an even number.
# Note: Set src_image_size_w and src_image_size_h based on the actual image width and height. If these parameters are left unconfigured and are set to 0, the width and height defined in the network input are used.
# src_image_size_w :0
# src_image_size_h :0

# Horizontal and vertical coordinates of the crop start. The width and height defined in the network input are used as the crop size.
# Type: uint13
# Value range: [0, 4096]. For YUV420SP_U8 images, the value must be an even number.
# Note: load_start_pos_w plus the width defined in the network input must be less than or equal to src_image_size_w. load_start_pos_h plus the height defined in the network input must be less than or equal to src_image_size_h.
# load_start_pos_w :0
# load_start_pos_h :0

# Padded value in the C direction
# Type: float16
# Value range: [–65504, +65504]
# cpadding_value :0.0

# R/B or U/V channel exchange enable before CSC
# Type: bool
# Value: true or false
# rbuv_swap_switch :false

# RGBA->ARGB and YUVA->AYUV exchange switch before CSC
# Type: bool
# Value: true or false
# ax_swap_switch :false

# Single line mode switch (in this mode, only the first line after crop is processed)
# Type: bool
# Value: true or false
# single_line_mode :false

# Resize or crop by the AIPP (reserved)
# Type: bool
# Value: true or false. The value true indicates resize, and the value false indicates crop.
# resize :true

#======== Mean reduction and multiplication coefficient settings =========
# The calculation rules are as follows:
# For uint8->uint8, this function is bypassed.
# For uint8->int8: pixel_out_chx(i) = pixel_in_chx(i) – mean_chn_i
# For uint8->fp16: pixel_out_chx(i) = [pixel_in_chx(i) – mean_chn_i – min_chn_i] x var_reci_chn

# Mean value of channel n
# Type: uint8
Value range: [0, 255]
# mean_chn_0 :0
# mean_chn_1 :0
# mean_chn_2 :0

# Minimum value of channel n
# Type: float16
# Value range: [–65504, +65504]
# min_chn_0 :0.0
# min_chn_1 :0.0
# min_chn_2 :0.0

# Channel n standard deviation or reciprocal of (Max – Min)
# Type: float16
# Value range: [–65504, +65504]
# var_reci_chn_0 :1.0
# var_reci_chn_1 :1.0
# var_reci_chn_2 :1.0

#==================CSC parameter settings ===================
# If the CSC switch is set to false, this function is bypassed.
# If the number of input images channels is 4, the first channel is ignored.
# YUV to BGR:
# | B |   | matrix_r0c0 matrix_r0c1 matrix_r0c2 | | Y - input_bias_0 |
# | G | = | matrix_r1c0 matrix_r1c1 matrix_r1c2 | | U - input_bias_1 | >> 8
# | R |   | matrix_r2c0 matrix_r2c1 matrix_r2c2 | | V - input_bias_2 |
# BGR to YUV:
# | Y |   | matrix_r0c0 matrix_r0c1 matrix_r0c2 | | B |        | output_bias_0 |
# | U | = | matrix_r1c0 matrix_r1c1 matrix_r1c2 | | G | >> 8 + | output_bias_1 |
# | V |   | matrix_r2c0 matrix_r2c1 matrix_r2c2 | | R |        | output_bias_2 |

# Elements in a 3 x 3 CSC matrix 
# Type: int16
# Value range: [–32768, +32767]
# matrix_r0c0 :298
# matrix_r0c1 :516
# matrix_r0c2 :0
# matrix_r1c0 :298
# matrix_r1c1 :-100
# matrix_r1c2 :-208
# matrix_r2c0 :298
# matrix_r2c1 :0
# matrix_r2c2 :409

# Output offset for RGB to YUV conversion
# Type: uint8
Value range: [0, 255]
# output_bias_0 :16
# output_bias_1 :128
# output_bias_2 :128

# Input offset for YUV to RGB conversion
# Type: uint8
Value range: [0, 255]
# input_bias_0 :16
# input_bias_1 :128
# input_bias_2 :128

quantization-configuration.html.title: Quantization Configuration
quantization-configuration.html.body:
Quantization Configuration
With  Quantization  enabled during offline model conversion （for details, see 5.2.1.1 "Adding a Custom Model Component"）, after the model conversion is complete, you can view the parameter configurations in the  convertModel.log  file of the project.
Format of the Configuration File

The weight, offset, and data quantization of convolution and fully connected operators with or without offset are supported. The scalar weight and vector weight are supported.
The multiple network input scenario is supported. Images （IMAGE） and binary files (BINARY) are supported.

Images （IMAGE） can be in .jpg, .png, or .bmp format.
Table 1  describes the supported formats of binary files （BINARY）.
Table  1  Binary file formats

Offset

Type

Value

Description



0000

32bit int

magic

magic number


0004

32bit int

50

input num


0008

32bit int

3

input channels


0012

32bit int

28

input height


0016

32bit int

28

input width


...

float

126

pixel






 NOTE:The header of binary file contains 20 bytes with five int numbers. The first is  510  （magic_num）, which is used for verification. The other four numbers are  n,  c,  h, and  w. Data following them are of the float type. The data records are equal to the value of (n*c*h*w). For non-4D data, the data needs to be supplemented to four dimensions and the value of the supplemented dimension is  1.  





Templates of the Configuration File 
The name of the quantization configuration file is user-defined. For details about the file content, see the following templates:

Single-input scenario （IMAGE）
device:USE_CPU
quantize_algo:HALF_OFFSET
weight_type:VECTOR_TYPE
preprocess_parameter:
{
input_type:IMAGE
image_format:BGR
input_file_path:'calibration/image_set'
mean_value:104.0
mean_value:117.0
mean_value:123.0
standard_deviation:1.0
}

Multi-input scenario （IMAGE+BINARY）
device:USE_CPU
quantize_algo:HALF_OFFSET
weight_type:VECTOR_TYPE
preprocess_parameter:
{
input_type:IMAGE
image_format:BGR
input_file_path:'calibration/image_set'
mean_value:104.0
mean_value:117.0
mean_value:123.0
standard_deviation:1.0
}
preprocess_parameter:
{
input_type:BINARY 
input_file_path:'calibration/img_info.bin'
}

Multi-input scenario （IMAGE+BINARY）, including all parameters
device:USE_CPU
quantize_algo:HALF_OFFSET
weight_type:VECTOR_TYPE
bin:150
type:KL
inference_with_data_quantized:false
inference_with_weight_quantized:true
super_parameter:
{
min_percentile:PERCENTILE_HIGH
max_percentile:PERCENTILE_MID
start_ratio:0.7
end_ratio:1.3
step_ratio:0.01
}
exclude_op:'fc1000'
batch_count:50
preprocess_parameter:
{
input_type:IMAGE
image_format:BGR
input_file_path:'calibration/image_set'
mean_value:104.0
mean_value:117.0
mean_value:123.0
standard_deviation:1.0
}
preprocess_parameter:
{
input_type:BINARY 
input_file_path:'calibration/img_info.bin'
}



 NOTE:When using this configuration file, set the required parameters as required. The parameters in the preceding templates are only recommended settings. Generally, the recommended settings do not need to be modified （except the input file setting）.  

Parameters in the Configuration File
The global setting parameters are described as follows.
Table  2  device

Name

Inference mode


Type

enum


Value Range

USE_CPU


Description

USE_CPU: Uses the CPU for inference.


Note

Currently, the CPU is used for quantization inference.


Recommended Setting

USE_CPU





Table  3  quantize_algo

Name

Quantization mode


Type

enum


Value Range

NON_OFFSET/HALF_OFFSET


Description

There are two quantization mapping formulas:
With offset: q_uint8 = round(d_float/scale) – offsetWithout offset: q_int8 = round(d_float/scale)
The weight and data are involved in the mapping.
NON_OFFSET: The weight and data use the without-offset mode.HALF_OFFSET: The data uses the with-offset mode, and the weight uses the without-offset mode.


Note

Both NON_OFFSET and HALF_OFFSET modes are supported.


Recommended Setting

HALF_OFFSET





Table  4  weight_type

Name

Weight quantization mode


Type

enum


Value Range

VECTOR_TYPE/SCALAR_TYPE


Description

For a convolution operator, it may have multiple convolution cores, and the corresponding quantization parameters may be different.
VECTOR_TYPE: Each convolution core uses a separate group of quantization parameters.SCALAR_TYPE: Multiple convolution cores use the same group of quantization parameters.


Note

VECTOR_TYPE is recommended.


Recommended Setting

VECTOR_TYPE





Table  5  preprocess_parameter

Name

Preprocessing and input parameters


Type

Struct


Value Range

Including input_type, image_format, input_file_path, mean_value, and standard_deviation


Description

Preprocessing and input settings


Note

The number of preprocess_parameter parameters must be the same as the number of operators input to the network.


Recommended Setting

None





Table  6  input_type

Name

Input data format


Type

enum


Value Range

IMAGE/BINARY


Description

Input type
IMAGE: image formatBINARY: binary format


Note

Configure the value as required.


Recommended Setting

None





Table  7  image_format

Name

Order of the three image input channels


Type

enum


Value Range

BGR/RGB


Description

Order of the three image input channels during model training


Note

This parameter needs to be set for IMAGE input. This parameter is determined based on the order of the input channels during network training. Generally, the order is BGR during network training.


Recommended Setting

BGR





Table  8  input_file_path

Name

Address of the input data


Type

string


Value Range

The path cannot contain Chinese characters, special characters, or spaces.


Description

Folder or file to be quantified


Note

Set this parameter based on the actual network configuration.
For IMAGE input, specify the folder.For BINARY input, specify the file.


Recommended Setting

Set this parameter to the image folder or binary file as required.





Table  9  mean_value

Name

Mean value for image preprocessing


Type

float


Value Range

[0, 255.0]


Description

Mean value of a channel for image preprocessing 


Note

This parameter needs to be set for IMAGE input. The count of mean values is determined by the channel count. Three mean values need to be configured for the RGB channels as follows:
mean_value: 104.0
mean_value: 117.0
mean_value: 123.0


Recommended Setting

None





Table  10  standard_deviation

Name

Standard deviation for image preprocessing


Type

float


Value Range

[0, FLOAT_MAX]


Description

Standard deviation for image preprocessing


Note

This parameter needs to be set for IMAGE input. One standard deviation is used for multiple channels.
If the input range is beyond the range that can be represented by the float type, the quantization precision of the model cannot be guaranteed.
If 0 ≤ standard_deviation ≤ 0.00001, the value of standard_deviation is 1.0.


Recommended Setting

1.0: The image value range (Original image value – Mean value) does not change. 255.0: If the image value range is [0, 255], the value can be condensed to [0, 1.0].)





Table  11  bin

Name

Data range of the mapping histogram


Type

uint32


Value Range

[0, 1000]


Description

Data range of the histogram statistics


Note

The statistics histogram is required during the calculation of scatter. The value of this parameter determines the maximum value of histogram statistics. If this parameter is not set or set to 0, the default value 150 is used.


Recommended Setting

100/150/200/250





Table  12  type

Name

Type of the divergence calculation indicator 


Type

enum


Value Range

KL/SYMKL/JSD


Description

KL: Kullback-Leibler Divergence; SYMKL: Symmetric Kullback-Leibler Divergence; JSD: Jensen-Shannon Divergence


Note

Different divergence types correspond to different calculation methods. The default value is KL.


Recommended Setting

None





Table  13  inference_with_data_quantized

Name

Whether to use the quantized data as the inference input 


Type

bool


Value Range

true/false


Description

Whether to use the quantized data as the inference input 


Note

When this parameter is set to true, the quantization of the input data is simulated. The default value is false. 


Recommended Setting

false





Table  14  inference_with_weight_quantized

Name

Whether to use the quantized data as the inference input 


Type

bool


Value Range

true/false


Description

Whether to use the quantized data as the inference input 


Note

When this function is enabled, the quantization and de-quantization of the weight data are simulated. The default value is true.


Recommended Setting

true





Table  15  super_parameter

Name

Searches parameters.


Type

Struct


Value Range

Including min_percentile, max_percentile, start_ratio, end_ratio, and step_ratio


Description

Searches parameters.


Note

You are advised to retain the default value.


Recommended Setting

None





Table  16  min_percentile

Name

Position for searching for the minimum number


Type

enum


Value Range

PERCENTILE_HIGH/PERCENTILE_MID/PERCENTILE_LOW


Description

Determines the minimum number to be used. For example, if there are 100 numbers, the value 1.0 indicates that number 0 (100 – 100 x 1.0) is used as the minimum number, that is, the first smallest number.


Note

PERCENTILE_HIGH: 1.0
PERCENTILE_MID: 0.99999
PERCENTILE_LOW: 0.9999


Recommended Setting

PERCENTILE_HIGH





Table  17  max_percentile

Name

Position for searching for the maximum number


Type

enum


Value Range

PERCENTILE_HIGH/PERCENTILE_MID/PERCENTILE_LOW


Description

Determines the maximum number to be used. For example, if there are 100 numbers, the value 1.0 indicates that number 0 (100 – 100 x 1.0) is used as the maximum number, that is, the first largest number.


Note

PERCENTILE_HIGH: 1.0
PERCENTILE_MID: 0.99999
PERCENTILE_LOW: 0.9999


Recommended Setting

PERCENTILE_MID





Table  18  start_ratio, end_ratio, and step_ratio 

Name

See the Description.


Type

float


Value Range

end_ratio > start_ratio > 0 and step_ratio > 0 (If the input range is beyond the range that can be represented by the float type, the quantization precision of the model cannot be guaranteed.)


Description

start_ratio indicates the search start. end_ratio indicates the search end. step_ratio indicates the search step. 


Note

After d_max and d_min are found in the algorithm, the ranges taken before and after d_max and d_min are determined based on start_ratio and end_ratio. Then, the step incremented each time is determined by step_ratio. For example: 
If d_max = 100, start_ratio = 0.8, end_ratio = 1.2, and step_ratio = 0.01, the defined search range before and after d_max are 80 (100 x 0.8) and 120 (100 x 1.2) at a step of 1 (100 x 0.01). That is, there are 41 d_max search values in total.


Recommended Setting

The following two sets of settings are recommended:
start_ratio = 0.7, end_ratio = 1.3, step_ratio = 0.01start_ratio = 0.3, end_ratio = 1.7, step_ratio = 0.01





Table  19  batch_count

Name

Number of batches of images processed in the quantization calibration set


Type

uint32


Value Range

[0, UINT32_MAX)


Description

Determines the number of batches of images processed in the quantization calibration set.


Note

If this parameter is not set or set to 0, all images in the calibration set are used. If the value is greater than 0, the smaller one in the total number of images in the calibration set path and the value of this parameter is used as the actual number of images in the calibration set. It is recommended that the number of images in the calibration set do not exceed 500.


Recommended Setting

None





Table  20  exclude_op

Name

Quantization operator blacklist


Type

string


Value Range

Operator name


Description

The operator indicated by this parameter is not quantified.


Note

Only Conv, FC, and DepthWiseConv operators are supported.To blacklist multiple operators, multiple exclude_op parameters need to be set. Each parameter occupies a line. For example:exclude_op:'aaa'
exclude_op:'bbb'



Recommended Setting

None
